In CRM Analytics, data integration involves gathering and preparing the Salesforce and external data you want to analyze. External data is data that resides outside of the Salesforce org that you use for Analytics.

Data preparation is the process of transforming your data into a form thatâ€™s meaningful and valuable to the people consuming it. You can define data preparation logic that combines data from two data sources and cleans up inconsistencies.

Recipes allow you to prepare your data before loading it into datasets. You can clean, aggregate, and transform your data using recipes. Data sync pulls data from the data source in advance and stores it in connected objects inside CRM Analytics.

To set up access to source data, create a connection. Run its data sync to extract the data from each selected object in the data source and store it in the corresponding CRM Analytics connected object.

Run the recipe to create datasets. Continue to run them to refresh the data. You can run data sync and recipes on demand or schedule them to run on an ongoing basis.

A dataset is a collection of related data that can be viewed in a tabular format. The data can come from many sources, including Salesforce objects, external data sources, and even other datasets.

To populate datasets with data from data sources, you can import the data directly from the source or extract the data from the source and prepare it before loading it into a dataset.

Before building your data integration solution, think about the use case you want to analyze and the data you need to get you there. Consider expected behavior and limitations to integrate data into datasets.
